description:
# Why

bl-ffb4 routes state-branch ops through .balls/state-repo/ when master_url is set, but cmd_sync's state-leg presence gate still asks the project root whether the state remote exists:

    let state_present = if state_remote == remote {
        code_present
    } else {
        git::git_has_remote(&store.root, &state_remote)
    };

In master_url mode the state-repo carries the hub remote — `origin` inside .balls/state-repo/.git/config — and the project root carries only the user's code remotes (and might carry none at all, e.g. the bridge clone in the multi-repo proxy pattern documented under bl-bfb7). So the gate silently skips the state push in exactly the topology master_url was built to enable.

The bl-ffb4 integration test `fresh_clone_with_master_url_auto_provisions_on_prime` does not catch this because clone_from_remote provisions an origin on the teammate; the check passes for the wrong reason.

# Concrete fix

The presence check should run against state_worktree_dir(), not store.root. With master_url set the state-repo always has `origin` (it's how ensure() materializes it), so the check effectively becomes "the state-repo exists," which is the right invariant.

# Scope

- src/commands/sync.rs: redirect the state-leg presence gate to state_worktree_dir() when master_url is set (or unconditionally — git_has_remote in the state-repo is the right question in both modes)
- Add a test where master_url is set and the project has no `origin`: bl sync must still push balls/tasks to the hub
